<sect1 id="ISODayOfWeekFromDate">
  <title>ISODayOfWeekFromDate</title>

  <para><emphasis role="bold">STD.Date.ISODayOfWeekFromDate<indexterm>
      <primary>STD.Date.ISODayOfWeekFromDate</primary>
    </indexterm><indexterm>
      <primary>Date.ISODayOfWeekFromDate</primary>
    </indexterm><indexterm>
      <primary>ISODayOfWeekFromDate</primary>
    </indexterm>(</emphasis> <emphasis>date</emphasis> <emphasis
  role="bold">)</emphasis></para>

  <informaltable colsep="1" frame="all" rowsep="1">
    <tgroup cols="2">
      <colspec colwidth="80.50pt" />

      <colspec />

      <tbody>
        <row>
          <entry><emphasis>date</emphasis></entry>

          <entry>The date (in Date_t format) for which to determine the day of
          week. </entry>
        </row>

        <row>
          <entry>Return:</entry>

          <entry>A INTEGER value in the range 1 to 7 representing the day of
          the week, where 1 = Monday.</entry>
        </row>
      </tbody>
    </tgroup>
  </informaltable>

  <para>The <emphasis role="bold">ISODayOfWeekFromDate</emphasis> function
  returns an INTEGER representing the day of the week indicated by the given
  date in ISO-8601. The date must be in the Gregorian calendar after the year
  1600.</para>

  <para>Example:</para>

  <programlisting format="linespecific">IMPORT STD;
STD.Date.ISODayOfWeekFromDate(20140130); // returns 4 (indicating Thursday)</programlisting>

  <para></para>
</sect1>
